Owlman 2023-02-19 9:00 AM
Yeah, it’s tough. Really a case of can you separate the art from the artist
Owlman 2023-02-19 9:23 AM
I was debating writing anything at all, but after collecting my thoughts, I want to put them down in writing, so here they are. This is a horror movie, and so please only read if you are ok with some horror movie elements, and spoilers. I am not joking, this is your warning. Anyway, my thoughts on Winnie the Pooh: Blood and Honey. First off, it’s intense. I was expecting a fairly bad horror movie with some cheap scares, but overall just a “scary” movie that’s more funny than anything. It is not that, at all. First off, while it’s obviously a budget film, it’s pretty well done. The sets are good, the actors and actresses aren’t great, but I’ve seen worse, and the the camera angles are not terrible. Some stuff is kinda sloppy, but there are some cool shots. Overall, for a directorial debut on a budget of less than $100,000, it’s pretty good. Definitely better than I expected. The plot is ok, but it’s got the horror movie curse of bad decisions. Some things however are inexcusable. For instance, forgetting you have a gun, but when you realize you do have it, not telling the person you give it to it only has 1 bullet. Also, the phones disappear with no explanation, as well as some other things that just do not make a lot of sense. I get that you wanna rescue people, but maybe, just maybe, you should leave and come back with the police. And if you fight a bear in the middle of the road, don’t attack one at a time. Now, as for horror, I appreciate they took the story seriously. I was worried they would do to much backstory or try and play some elements for humor, but they don’t. I don’t remember a single joke actually. Also, they realized traditional “building suspense” horror would work, so they really, really leaned into the violence. It is a very, very gruesome movie and hard to watch. I think they did this on purpose, which I’ll get to later, and while I understand and can appreciate why, I was not prepared, and it made me very uncomfortable in places. (edited)
Owlman 2023-02-19 9:32 AM
Now to the things I liked. First off, there isn’t a happy ending. All but one character dies, and the only one that gets left is because they are obviously doing a sequel. Also, the sets are incredible. Besides the major plot holes they create, they look really good. And the special effects are very realistic, a little too realistic in fact. Despite the good though, it’s a hard movie to watch. Overall, while it’s not a good movie, or even one I’d watch again (unless I was with friends) it’s not awful. And I appreciate that it exists. Obviously, the director knew this would stir up controversy, and controversy sells. Which this has. While some of the creative choices are hard to watch, it worked, and it’s definitely something I’ll remember. I believe art should exist for the sake of art, that it doesn’t need a lesson or message to be worthy of existing, and this movie embodies that. It is a film that exists because it can, and like Adam, Check Please, I feel that all art, no matter how bad it is, deserves to exist. Though you may not “get it” or even think its bad, it still makes you think. That means the art did its job, and for that, it deserves respect (edited)
